## Part V: Meta-Observations

### On the Process

This document was not written in one pass. It was produced through a multi-turn dialogue involving proposal, critique, revision, defense, and synthesis. The corrections from external audit were not cosmetic — they changed formal statements (Conjecture N → N'), identified definitional errors (Byzantine sheaf on line graph, not original graph), and added crucial methodology (Takens embedding for Candidate 1, three-way comparison design).

**What this implies:** Single-author research proposals have blind spots that structured adversarial review corrects. The process of earning claims (Principle A) is not just philosophical — it produces materially better research designs.

### On the Map vs. the Territory

This document is a **map of productive territory**, not a claim that every candidate will yield results. The value of the map is in making precise questions askable, not in predicting which answers will be found. The candidates that survive first contact with computation or proof will be different from the ones that don't — and that's the point.

### On What Constitutes a Discovery

The candidates span a range of discovery types:
- **Empirical** (Candidate 1: predict a topological property, test it).
- **Conceptual** (Candidate 4: show sheaves organize multi-modal fusion in a way transformers don't capture).
- **Methodological** (Candidate 8: provide a new tool for Byzantine detection).
- **Unificatory** (Combination 1: connect number theory to algebraic geometry through zeta zeros).

All four types are genuine discoveries. The empirical ones have the clearest verification criteria. The conceptual and unificatory ones may prove more durable.

